(535, 1, '2014-10-30 11:41:19', '2014-10-30 11:41:19', '<h3>Neonatal Unit at Bradford Royal Infirmary</h3>\r\n<p>Bowman Riley Architects designed the expansion of the existing Neonatal unit at Bradford Royal Infirmary for Bradford Teaching Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust. The unit cares for in excess of 500 babies each year and it is a figure which is continually rising. This fact, along with the increasing demand for the highly specialist care the unit offers, have been the key factors in the decision to expand.</p>\r\n<p>Our brief was multifaceted with four key drivers to:-</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>provide four additional intensive care cot spaces</li>\r\n<li>improve the way the unit functions ensuring flexibility within clinical areas</li>\r\n<li>offering differing levels of care, improving room adjacencies, room areas and the</li>\r\n<li>delineation between staff and visitor spaces</li>\r\n<li>improve the quality of the environment</li>\r\n<li>enable the use of existing specialist equipment and staff to their full potential</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>We have produced a scheme that delivers on all fronts in compliance with Department of Health guidance and in consultation with clinical staff. Three extensions increase the footprint of the building by circa 350m complemented by significant internal refurbishment of the existing building.</p>\r\n<p>We planned the construction works around a fully operational 24/7 unit through the generation of a highly detailed phasing plan, working closely with the project and clinical teams.</p>', 'Bradford Teaching Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust', 'Bowman Riley Architects designed the expansion of the existing Neonatal unit at Bradford Royal Infirmary for Bradford Teaching Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust.', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'bradford-teaching-hospitals-nhs-foundation-trust', '', '', '2014-10-30 11:47:35', '2014-10-30 11:47:35', '', 0, 'http://92.60.114.159/~bowmanriley/?post_type=casestudies&#038;p=535', 0, 'casestudies', '', 0),
(536, 1, '2014-10-30 11:56:44', '2014-10-30 11:56:44', '<h3>Ward Development and Public Concourse, Bradford Royal Infirmary</h3>\r\n<p>Following on from healthcare director, Steve Batsons design of a modular 60 bed ward as part of a Phase 1 development at Bradford Royal Infirmary, Bowman Riley was commissioned to design a 6,000m Phase 2 development comprising a new general medical ward, paediatric ward and public concourse.</p>\r\n<p>Located opposite the hospitals main entrance, the new building is arranged over three storeys and will provide clinical staff, patients and visitors with improved facilities and services. The public concourse on the ground floor will comprise a new reception and patient advice and liaison services in addition to a caf, restaurant, pharmacy and retail units.</p>\r\n<p>Designed around two new hospital wards on two levels, a general medical ward on first floor and state of the art paediatric ward on the second floor, a central courtyard will provide access to outdoor space to enhance the patient experience.</p>\r\n<p>The paediatric ward will provide a dedicated space for clinical staff to treat children with both short term and long term medical needs. The ward will also comprise a new reception and waiting area, activity room, adolescent lounge, physiotherapy room, sensory room, school room and parents room to facilitate the wellbeing of both patients and visitors.</p>', 'Bradford Teaching Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust', 'Following on from healthcare director, Steve Batsons design of a modular 60 bed ward as part of a Phase 1 development at Bradford Royal Infirmary, Bowman Riley was commissioned to design a 6,000m Phase 2 development comprising a new general medical ward, paediatric ward and public concourse.', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'bradford-teaching-hospitals-nhs-foundation-trust-2', '', '', '2014-10-30 11:56:44', '2014-10-30 11:56:44', '', 0, 'http://92.60.114.159/~bowmanriley/?post_type=casestudies&#038;p=536', 0, 'casestudies', '', 0),
